For Linux, need to configure the local GIT client with a username and email address
  $ git config --global user.name "your_github_username"
  $ git config --global user.email "your_github_email"
  $ git config -l

Once Git configured, we can begin using it to access GitHub. Example
  $git clone <repo name>

Now cache the given record in your computer to remember the token:
 $ git config --global credential.helper cache

If needed, anytime you can delete the cache record by:
 $ git config --global --unset credential.helper
 $ git config --system --unset credential.helper

 $ git clone <repo name>
 $ git status 
 $ git add . (we can give all or file name, add to staging area)
 $ git commit -m "Commit Message"
 $ git push origin master  //Push to remote Repo

 $ git pull //Pull latest from Remote Repo
 
// How to use gitignore
  create a file name as .gitignore
  touch .gitignore
  add the file/dir which is not required to push it to remote
